<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="24" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="1.[824,1475,276,1801]" pageId="1" pageNumber="24">
<emphasis box="[862,1003,827,851]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="24">Iconography.</emphasis>
– 
<bibRefCitation author="MOGGRIDGE" box="[1028,1224,827,851]" firstAuthor="MOGGRIDGE" journalOrPublisher="London" pageId="1" pageNumber="24" refId="ref2556" refString="MOGGRIDGE, J. - T. (1864). Contributions to the flora of Mentone and to a winter flora of the Riviera, including the coast from Marseilles to Genoa. Fasc. I (Plate I-XXV). London." title="Contributions to the flora of Mentone and to a winter flora of the Riviera, including the coast from Marseilles to Genoa" type="book" year="1864">MOGGRIDGE (1864</bibRefCitation>
: plate XXV, sub 
<taxonomicName authority="Gren." authorityName="Gren." class="Liliopsida" family="Liliaceae" genus="Fritillaria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Liliales" pageId="1" pageNumber="24" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="delphinensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="24">F. delphinensis</emphasis>
Gren.
</taxonomicName>
?) published a plate which illustrates specimens gathered “from a mountain not far from Giandola in the Sospello valley” (
<figureCitation box="[1015,1077,923,947]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="4.[113,136,1926,1946]" captionTargetBox="[113,1490,275,1881]" captionTargetId="figure-122@4.[395,1281,381,1881]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Fig. 3. – Iconography of “Fritillaria delphinensis Gren.?”, published by MOGGRIDGE (1864: plate XXV), which is also original material for F. delphinensis f. moggridgei Planch." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5708588" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5708588/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="24">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[824,1475,276,1801]" pageId="1" pageNumber="24">
In the protologue, 
<bibRefCitation author="PLANCHON" box="[1053,1239,959,983]" firstAuthor="PLANCHON" journalOrPublisher="Bull. Soc. Bot. France" pageId="1" pageNumber="24" pagination="96 - 124" part="20" refId="ref2703" refString="PLANCHON, J. E. (1873). Sur les especes de fritillaries de France, a propos des icones et d'un manuscrit inedit de Pierre De Belleval. Bull. Soc. Bot. France 20: 96 - 124." title="Sur les especes de fritillaries de France, a propos des icones et d'un manuscrit inedit de Pierre De Belleval" type="journal article" year="1873">PLANCHON (1873)</bibRefCitation>
quoted, for this taxon, several type localities (gatherings in Herb. Thuret, G-BU) from the Maritime Alps and also the Moggridge's iconography cited above, which is consequently original material for the name. Moreover, we traced in G-BU, MPU and FI specimens, from the cited localities, that completely fit with the protologue and then can be considered as original material too (syntypes). Among these, only one specimen, conserved in G-BU, is labelled as 
<taxonomicName box="[824,981,1215,1239]" class="Liliopsida" family="Liliaceae" genus="Fritillaria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Liliales" pageId="1" pageNumber="24" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="delphinensis">
<emphasis box="[824,981,1215,1239]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="24">F. delphinensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
γ 
<emphasis box="[1009,1130,1215,1239]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="24">moggridgei</emphasis>
[manu Planch.] (January, 1873). The complete individual on the left is chosen as the lectotype.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[824,1475,276,1801]" pageId="1" pageNumber="24">
<emphasis box="[862,1087,1283,1307]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="24">Taxonomic discussion</emphasis>
. – This taxon was treated, in the past, in different ways: as a subspecies (i.e., 
<bibRefCitation author="RIX" box="[1250,1357,1315,1339]" firstAuthor="RIX" journalOrPublisher="Bot. J. Linn. Soc." pageId="1" pageNumber="24" pagination="356" part="76" refId="ref2747" refString="RIX, E. M. (1978). Short notes (Liliaceae). Bot. J. Linn. Soc. 76: 356." title="Short notes (Liliaceae)" type="journal article" year="1978">RIX, 1978</bibRefCitation>
), a variety (i.e., 
<bibRefCitation author="FIORI" box="[881,1007,1347,1371]" firstAuthor="FIORI" journalOrPublisher="Firenze." pageId="1" pageNumber="24" pagination="248 - 250" part="1" refId="ref2487" refString="FIORI, A. (1923). Nuova Fl. Analitica Italia 1: 248 - 250. Firenze." title="Nuova Fl. Analitica Italia" type="journal article" year="1923">FIORI, 1923</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="PIGNATTI" box="[1025,1190,1347,1371]" firstAuthor="PIGNATTI" journalOrPublisher="Edagricole." pageId="1" pageNumber="24" pagination="360 - 361" part="3" refId="ref2684" refString="PIGNATTI, S. (1982). Fl. Italia 3: 360 - 361. Edagricole." title="Fl. Italia" type="journal article" year="1982">PIGNATTI, 1982</bibRefCitation>
) or fully synonymic (i.e., 
<bibRefCitation author="AESCHIMANN" box="[824,1086,1379,1403]" etAl="&amp; al." firstAuthor="AESCHIMANN" journalOrPublisher="Zanichelli, Bologna" pageId="1" pageNumber="24" refId="ref2375" refString="AESCHIMANN, D., K. LAUBER, D. MARTIN MOSER &amp; J. P. THEURILLAT (2004). Fl. Alpina 2. Zanichelli, Bologna." title="Fl. Alpina 2" type="book" year="2004">AESCHIMANN &amp; al., 2004</bibRefCitation>
) with 
<taxonomicName box="[1155,1289,1379,1403]" class="Liliopsida" family="Liliaceae" genus="Fritillaria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Liliales" pageId="1" pageNumber="24" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="tubiformis">
<emphasis box="[1155,1289,1379,1403]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="24">F. tubiformis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The study of the selected lectotype and of the other available original material clearly shows that this taxon is closer to 
<taxonomicName box="[1258,1394,1443,1467]" class="Liliopsida" family="Liliaceae" genus="Fritillaria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Liliales" pageId="1" pageNumber="24" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="tubiformis">
<emphasis box="[1258,1394,1443,1467]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="24">F. tubiformis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
than to any other European species. However, the two seem to be very distinct for many character-states. Our preliminary results confirm this view. Nowadays, there is some doubt about the relations between 
<taxonomicName box="[979,1320,1572,1596]" class="Liliopsida" family="Liliaceae" genus="Fritillaria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Liliales" pageId="1" pageNumber="24" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="subSpecies" species="tubiformis" subSpecies="moggridgei">
<emphasis box="[979,1116,1572,1596]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="24">F. tubiformis</emphasis>
subsp. 
<emphasis box="[1197,1320,1572,1596]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="24">moggridgei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Adam" authorityName="Adam" class="Liliopsida" family="Liliaceae" genus="Fritillaria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Liliales" pageId="1" pageNumber="24" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="collina">
<emphasis box="[1373,1474,1572,1596]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="24">F. collina</emphasis>
Adam
</taxonomicName>
(= 
<taxonomicName authority="M. Bieb." authorityName="M. Bieb." box="[928,1107,1604,1628]" class="Liliopsida" family="Liliaceae" genus="Fritillaria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Liliales" pageId="1" pageNumber="24" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="lutea">
<emphasis box="[928,1007,1604,1628]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="24">F. lutea</emphasis>
M. Bieb.
</taxonomicName>
). The latter species, widespread in Caucasus (
<bibRefCitation author="RIX" box="[940,1045,1636,1660]" firstAuthor="RIX" journalOrPublisher="The Fritillaria Group of the Alpine Garden Society, United Kingdom" pageId="1" pageNumber="24" refId="ref2775" refString="RIX, E. M. (2001). Fritillaria. A revised classification. The Fritillaria Group of the Alpine Garden Society, United Kingdom." title="Fritillaria. A revised classification" type="book" year="2001">RIX, 2001</bibRefCitation>
), has yellow-greenish flowers and inner tepals with ciliate margins.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
